If people work in the entertainment industry as high-profile celebrities, then they wake up late and start their schedules past noon regularly. If people do not have regular 9-5 jobs, then they work in the entertainment industry as high-profile celebrities. All people who prefer working at home over going to the office every day do not have regular 9-5 jobs. Clay either both prefers to work at home over going to the office every day and makes his own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder, or he neither prefers to work at home over going to the office every day nor makes his own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder.
question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Clay neither prefers working at home over going to the office every day nor lives in California and attends yoga classes regularly.
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Make(x, y) ::: x makes y.
CeremonialGrade(x) ::: x is ceremonial-grade.
MatchaTea(x) ::: x is a matcha tea.
WakeUpLate(x) ::: x wakes up late.
StartSchedulePastNoon(x) ::: x starts his schedule past noon.
LiveIn(x, y) ::: x lives in y.
Attend(x, y) ::: x attends y.
WorkIn(x, y) ::: x works in y.
HighProfile(x) ::: x is a high-profile celebrity.
Regular9_5Job(x) ::: x has a regular 9-5 job.
Prefer(x, y) ::: x prefers y.
Premises:
∀x (∀y (Make(x, y) ∧ CeremonialGrade(y) ∧ MatchaTea(y)) → ¬(WakeUpLate(x) ∧ StartSchedulePastNoon(x))) ::: If people make their own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder, then they do not wake up late and start their schedules past noon regularly.
∀x (∀y (LiveIn(x, california) ∧ Attend(x, yogaClasses)) → Make(x, y)) ::: If people live in California and attend yoga classes regularly, then they make their own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder.
∀x (∀y (WorkIn(x, entertainmentIndustry) ∧ HighProfile(x)) → (WakeUpLate(x) ∧ StartSchedulePastNoon(x))) ::: If people work in the entertainment industry as high-profile celebrities, then they wake up late and start their schedules past noon regularly.
∀x (∀y (WorkIn(x, entertainmentIndustry) ∧ HighProfile(x)) → ¬Regular9_5Job(x)) ::: If people work in the entertainment industry as high-profile celebrities, then they do not have regular 9-5 jobs.
∀x (∀y (Prefer(x, workAtHome) ∧ Prefer(x, officeEveryDay)) → ¬Regular9_5Job(x)) ::: All people who prefer working at home over going to the office every day do not have regular 9-5 jobs.
∃y (∃x (Prefer(x, workAtHome) ∧ Make(x, y) ∧ CeremonialGrade(y) ∧ MatchaTea(y))) ∨ ¬(Prefer(clay, workAtHome) ∧ Make(clay, y) ∧ CeremonialGrade(y) ∧ MatchaTea(y)) ::: Clay either both prefers to work at home over going to the office every day and makes his own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder, or he neither prefers to work at home over going to the office every day nor makes his own matcha teas every morning with ceremonial-grade matcha powder.
Conclusion:
¬(Prefer(clay, workAtHome) ∧ LiveIn(clay, california) ∧ Attend(clay, yogaClasses)) ::: Clay neither prefers working at home over going to the office every day nor lives in California and attends yoga classes regularly.
------

context: If something can go underwater, then it enjoys water. All animals that can swim can go underwater. Either an animal can swim or it can walk. Animals that can walk travel on land. Animal(x) ::: x is an animal.
Swim(x) ::: x can swim.
Walk(x) ::: x can walk.
Travel(x, y) ::: x travels on y.
Splash(x, y) ::: x splashes y around.
Bask(x, y) ::: x basks in y.

∀x (Underwater(x) → Enjoy(x, water)) ::: If something can go underwater, then it enjoys water.
∀x (Animal(x) ∧ Swim(x) → Underwater(x)) ::: All animals that can swim can go underwater.
∀x (Animal(x) → (Swim(x) ∨ Walk(x))) ::: Either an animal can swim or it can walk.
∀x (Animal(x) ∧ Walk(x) → Travel(x, land)) ::: Animals that can walk travel on land.
∀x (Animal(x) ∧ Enjoy(x, water) → Splash(x, water)) ::: Animals that enjoy water splash water around.
∀x (Animal(x) ∧ Travel(x, land) → Enjoy(x, sun)) ::: Every animal that travels on land enjoys basking in the sun.
George ∧ Swim(george) ∧ Splash(george, water) ::: George splashes water around and can swim.
Liam ∧ (Animal(liam) ∧ Walk(liam) ∧ Enjoy(liam, water)) ⊕ ¬(Animal(liam) ∨ Enjoy(liam, water)) ::: Liam is either an animal that can walk and enjoys water, or is neither an animal that can walk nor enjoys water.
Conclusion:
Enjoy(george, sun) ::: George enjoys basking in the sun.
------

question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Volunteers who participate in natural disaster response receive intangible benefits for their work.
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Volunteer(x) ::: x is a volunteer.
IntangibleBenefits(x) ::: x receives intangible benefits for his/her work.
WorkRegularly(x) ::: x works regularly.
WorkAsNeeded(x) ::: x works on an as-needed basis.
Trained(x) ::: x is trained.
WorkInGroup(x) ::: x works in groups.
WorkIndividually(x) ::: x works individually.
EnvironmentalVolunteer(x) ::: x is an environmental volunteer.
Contribute(x, y) ::: x contributes toward y.
EnvironmentalManagement(x) ::: x is an example of environmental management.
EnvironmentalConservation(x) ::: x is an example of environmental conservation.
NaturalDisasterResponse(x) ::: x is an example of natural disaster response.
Premises:
∀x (Volunteer(x) → IntangibleBenefits(x)) ::: All volunteers receive intangible benefits for their work.
∀x (Volunteer(x) → (WorkRegularly(x) ⊕ WorkAsNeeded(x))) ::: Volunteers work regularly or on an as-needed basis.
∃x (Volunteer(x) ∧ Trained(x)) ::: Some volunteers are trained.
∀x (Volunteer(x) → (WorkInGroup(x) ⊕ WorkIndividually(x))) ::: Volunteers work in groups or individually.
∃x (EnvironmentalVolunteer(x) ∧ Contribute(x, environmentalManagement)) ::: Environmental volunteers contribute toward environmental management.
∃x (EnvironmentalVolunteer(x) ∧ Contribute(x, environmentalConservation)) ::: Environmental volunteers contribute toward environmental conservation.
∃x (NaturalDisasterResponse(x) ∧ WorkInGroup(x) ∧ WorkAsNeeded(x)) ::: Participating in natural disaster response is an example of volunteers working in groups on an as-needed basis.
Conclusion:
∃x (Volunteer(x) ∧ NaturalDisasterResponse(x) ∧ IntangibleBenefits(x)) ::: Volunteers who participate in natural disaster response receive intangible benefits for their work.
------
